Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Peel and grate the @ginger{1}. TIP: Use a teaspoon to easily scrape away the peel.

Trim the @green beans{150%g} and cut into 3 pieces. Peel the @sweet potato{1} and chop into 1cm cubes.

Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all).

Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the #pan{} from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #saucepan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the onion and cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir in the @Sri Lankan style curry powder{1%tbsp}, garlic and ginger and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @water for the sauce{100%ml}, @peanut butter{30%g}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and sweet potato. Bring to a simmer, then cover with a lid (or #foil{}).

Cook, stirring occasionally, until the sweet potato is just cooked, ~{10-15%minutes}. Add the green beans, cover again, then continue to cook until the beans are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, zest and halve the @lime{1/2}.

Heat a #small frying pan{} on medium heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @cashew nuts{25%g} and dry-fry, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Watch the cashews like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Once the beans are tender, remove your curry from the heat and add a squeeze of lime juice.

Stir through three quarters of the coriander. Season to taste with @salt{pinch} and @ground black pepper{pinch} if needed. Add a splash of water if it's a bit thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir in the lime zest, then share between your #bowls{}. Top with your sweet potato curry.

Scatter over the cashews and remaining coriander to finish. Enjoy!